{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","author_sig":"{\"payload\": \"\", \"payloadType\": \"application/vnd.rebar.authorship.v1+json\", \"signatures\": [{\"keyid\": \"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d\", \"sig\": \"\"}]}","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Context / Problem\n\nEven with the port defined (S2 [rebar:ce4d-c3ca-5412-4798]) and selection wired (S3\n[rebar:94f9-a9a0-7475-4e75]), the backend-neutral **core still names Jira concretely** — both by\nimporting the vendor mappers and by constructing the Jira transport inline. This story routes\n**every core consumer** through the `Backend` port so the core stops importing\n`adapters.jira.*` / the root vendor modules, and moves the Jira-specific logic the core inlined\n(ADF size-fitting, lossy status/parent rules, duplicated value-maps, and the misplaced\n`outbound_links` link-relation constant) into\n`adapters/jira/`. It changes **who calls what**, not where files live (physical relocation is S5\n[rebar:dfb9-d2d1-455d-48d9]).\n\n**Confirmed leak sites** (verified by grep against current `main`; the ADR §(a) list is stale —\nit names `baseline_shadow.py`, which does not exist, and omits `apply_inbound.py`):\n\nCore modules that import a vendor mapper:\n- `outbound_differ.py:63` — `from rebar_reconciler.outbound_fields import _map_local_to_jira_fields, _diff_fields`.\n- `inbound_differ.py:141` — `_map_jira_to_local_fields(...)` (inbound mapper).\n- `reconcile_check.py:70,75` — `_load_sibling(\"outbound_fields\", …)` / `_load_sibling(\"adf\", …)`.\n- `apply_inbound.py:49` — `from rebar_reconciler.outbound_fields import _map_local_to_jira_fields`.\n- `inbound_translate.py:323` — `lazy_load(_ADF_KEY_APPLIER, \"adf.py\")`.\n- `outbound_comments.py:84,100` — `lazy_load` of `adf.py` + `comment_limits.py`.\n- `outbound_links.py:42` — the vendor link-relation constant\n  `_RELATION_TO_JIRA_LINK: dict[str, tuple[str, bool]]` (the Jira-specific relation→link-type\n  map) lives **in this core module**. (Correction to an earlier draft: it is **not** a duplicate\n  of `acli_graph._RELATION_TO_JIRA_LINK` — grep confirms `acli_graph.py` no longer defines that\n  name; the `outbound_links.py:30` comment referencing `acli_graph` is **stale**, from a prior\n  cycle when the constant was hosted there. Today `outbound_links.py:42` is the *sole* definition.)\n  It is a Jira-vendor constant sitting in backend-neutral core, so it is single-sourced into\n  `adapters/jira/` here — no de-duplication is involved, just relocation of the one definition.\n- `apply_inbound_records.py:70,74` — the hardcoded `\"jira\"` **provider-identity** literals\n  (`\"jira\"` at `:70`, `creation_channel=\"jira\"` at `:74`) that a `RemoteRef`/`IdentityConvention`\n  replaces. (**Excluded:** `apply_inbound_records.py:156` — `validate_creation_channel(\"jira\")` —\n  is **not** a provider-identity literal but a **creation-channel vocabulary key** validated by\n  `rebar.reducer._version.validate_creation_channel`, which accepts a fixed enumerated string.\n  It is out of scope for the `RemoteRef` swap and stays as-is; conflating it with the provider\n  literals was an earlier-draft error.)\n\nCore transport/construction sites (moved here from S3 because they change the `_load_acli`\ncontract and its patched tests — that must land atomically with the rewire, not in the\ninfra-only S3):\n- `applier.py:443` and `applier.py:605` — both go through the **existing** `applier._load_acli`\n  seam (`applier.py:224`): evolve the seam + its `patch.object` tests.\n- `fetcher.py:371` — through the **existing** `fetcher._load_acli` seam (`fetcher.py:113`): same.\n- `run_differs.py:403` — **no `_load_acli` seam exists here.** It does a bare\n  `from rebar_reconciler import acli as acli_mod_for_comments` (module import) then constructs\n  `acli_mod_for_comments.AcliClient(jira_url=…, user=…, api_token=…)` at `:403` from\n  `acli_subprocess.resolve_jira_settings()`. So this site is a **distinct implementation step**:\n  route it directly through `select_backend(config).transport` (the `TicketTransport`) instead of\n  the module-level `AcliClient`, and — because there is **no existing patch target** for its\n  tests to hook — add a small `_load_acli`-equivalent seam (or inject the backend transport) that\n  the new test patches. The existing coverage relies on `acli_mod_for_comments` being a test fake\n  that only provides `AcliClient` (the comment at `run_differs.py:396` says exactly this); that\n  fake-injection point is replaced by patching the selected backend's transport. This site's new\n  seam + its test are called out as their own task below (they do not share applier/fetcher's\n  seam).\n- `_attestation.py:82` — via `build_acli_client_from_env` (`_attestation.py:41`): route through\n  the backend transport; update its construction path.\n\nExplicitly **not** leak sites: `differ.py`, `classify.py`, `binding_walk.py`, `reconcile.py`\n(they only use `jira_fields` as a local variable / payload-dict-key name — no vendor import);\nand `acli.py:145` (adapter-internal client construction — stays in the adapter, moves in S5).\n\n## Approach\n\nWork one site at a time behind held-out characterization tests that pin current reconcile\noutput. For each importer: call the mapper/sanitizer method on the selected `Backend` instead of\nimporting the vendor function, and delete the direct import. For the transport sites, two shapes:\n(1) `applier`/`fetcher` — evolve their **existing** `_load_acli` seams (`applier.py:224`,\n`fetcher.py:113`) and update their `patch.object(..., \"_load_acli\")` tests in the same change.\n**New return-value contract (pinned):** post-change, `_load_acli()` returns the selected\nbackend's **`TicketTransport` object directly** (i.e. `select_backend(config).transport`), *not*\nthe acli module. Call sites change from `acli_mod.AcliClient(jira_url=…, user=…, api_token=…)`\nto using the returned transport directly (no further `AcliClient(...)` construction).\n**Test-double migration surface — specified by property, not a brittle count (grep-verified\nagainst current `main`).** Every test that injects at the `_load_acli` seam is in scope,\nacross **three** injection styles: `patch.object(applier|fetcher, \"_load_acli\", …)` (~28\nfiles), `monkeypatch.setattr(…, \"_load_acli\", …)` (~5 files), and **direct attribute\nassignment** (`mod._load_acli = lambda: …` with save/restore — e.g.\n`conflict/test_parent_sync.py`, `mutate/test_comment_enrichment.py`, `mutate/test_link_sync.py`).\n**Plus** the integration double at `tests/integration/rebar_reconciler/jira_contract/_fakes.py`,\nwhich today returns a **module-shaped** `_FakeAcliModule` whose `.AcliClient(**kwargs)` yields a\n`FakeAcliClient`. Excluded (not seam injections, must **not** be migrated): the two files that\ndefine their *own* local `def _load_acli()` — `conflict/test_status_transition_rest.py` and\n`mutate/test_assignee_validation.py` — which a naive `grep -rl '_load_acli'` would wrongly\nsweep in. Because these exclusions/overlaps make a raw file count fragile, the story does **not**\nassert an exact `wc -l`; it asserts the migration *property* below. Each in-scope double is\nrepointed from a module exposing `AcliClient` to a **transport-shaped** double implementing the\n**exact `TicketTransport` surface defined in S2** — for the *fetcher* read path that surface is\n`search_issues`, `get_parent_map`, `get_comment_map`, `get_issuelinks_map` (the methods\n`fetcher.py:271,419,438,475,487,518,524` actually call), and for the *applier* write path the\ncreate/update/transition/`add_label`/`add_comment` methods — so `FakeAcliClient`'s existing\nfour-method fetcher surface is preserved, just delivered as a transport rather than via a module\n`.AcliClient` factory. Picking this concrete shape (vs.\nreturning a whole `Backend` and doing `_load_acli().transport` at call sites) is deliberate:\nit keeps every call site a bare `_load_acli()` and confines the doubles to the transport\nsurface. **Exception-class catch site (`apply_handlers.py:181`).** `apply_handlers.py:181`\ntoday does `except ctx.acli.AssigneeNotFoundError`, reaching the exception class *through* the\nacli module that `_load_acli()` currently returns (threaded in as `ctx.acli` from\n`applier.py:439,594`). Once `_load_acli()` returns a bare `TicketTransport`, that attribute no\nlonger exists and the catch would `AttributeError` on every assignee-soft-fail path. So this\nstory **adds `apply_handlers.py` to its edit-set**: import the class directly —\n`from rebar_reconciler.acli_subprocess import AssigneeNotFoundError` (defined at\n`acli_subprocess.py:147`, an adapter-internal module) — and rewrite the catch to\n`except AssigneeNotFoundError`, dropping the dependency on `ctx.acli` carrying exception\nclasses. (`ctx.acli`/`BatchApplyContext` is updated so no other site reads an exception class\noff the transport.) (2)\n`run_differs.py:403` and `_attestation.py:82` — these have **no `_load_acli` seam**;\n`run_differs` uses a bare module import + direct `AcliClient(...)`. For `run_differs`, introduce a\nnew seam (a `_load_acli`-equivalent or a backend-transport injection point) as an explicit\nprerequisite step, route the outbound-diff client through `select_backend(config).transport`, and\n**add a fresh test** that patches the new seam (there is no existing patch target to reuse — the\nold fake-injection was `acli_mod_for_comments` per `run_differs.py:396`). For `_attestation`,\nroute `build_acli_client_from_env` through the backend transport likewise. Relocate the inlined Jira logic — ADF size-fitting,\nlossy status/parent mapping, the duplicated priority/status value-maps, and the\n`outbound_links._RELATION_TO_JIRA_LINK` link-relation constant (`:42`, the sole definition\ntoday — a relocation, not a de-duplication) — into `adapters/jira/` so it is single-sourced\nbehind the mapper. Replace the `apply_inbound_records.py:70,74` `\"jira\"` provider literals with\n`RemoteRef`/`IdentityConvention` (leaving the `:156` `validate_creation_channel(\"jira\")`\nvocabulary key untouched).\n\n## Scope\n\n- Route the 8 core importer sites + 4 transport/construction sites above through the `Backend`\n  port.\n- Relocate ADF-sizing, lossy status/parent, duplicated value-maps, and the\n  `outbound_links._RELATION_TO_JIRA_LINK` link-relation constant (`:42`) into `adapters/jira/`\n  (single-sourced — a relocation of the one definition, not de-duplication).\n- Replace the `apply_inbound_records.py:70,74` `\"jira\"` provider literals with\n  `RemoteRef`/`IdentityConvention` (the `:156` `validate_creation_channel(\"jira\")` vocabulary key\n  is out of scope and unchanged).\n- Update the `_load_acli` seam tests in lockstep with the seam contract change — every test that\n  injects at the seam, across the **three** injection styles (`patch.object` ~28,\n  `monkeypatch.setattr` ~5, direct attribute assignment ~3) **plus** the integration `_fakes.py`\n  double, repointed from a module exposing `AcliClient` to a transport-shaped double. Specified by\n  the migration *property* (Approach + AC), **not** a brittle file count, and excluding the two\n  self-defining `def _load_acli()` files.\n- Rewrite `apply_handlers.py:181`'s `except ctx.acli.AssigneeNotFoundError` to catch the\n  directly-imported `acli_subprocess.AssigneeNotFoundError` (so the exception class no longer\n  rides on the transport object `_load_acli()` now returns).\n- **Out of scope:** physically moving `acli*`/`adf`/`outbound_fields`/`comment_limits` and the\n  loader/patch migration (S5); the registry (S3, prerequisite); the interface (S2, prerequisite).\n\n## Testing\n\n- **Tier:** integration + unit, RED-first held-out oracle.\n- **Characterization:** the full reconcile suite (outbound + inbound passes over fixture stores)\n  produces identical events/outcomes to pre-story `main` — the primary behavior-preserving guard.\n- **Neutrality gate:** a test/`grep` asserts **none** of the 12 rewired core modules import\n  `rebar_reconciler.adapters.jira.*` or the root vendor modules\n  (`outbound_fields`/`inbound_fields`/`adf`/`comment_limits`/`acli*`) and that no direct `AcliClient(` construction\n  remains outside the adapter.\n- **Unit:** ADF size-fitting invoked via the mapper still truncates at the Jira limit;\n  `apply_inbound_records` stamps a correct `RemoteRef`; `outbound_links` link relations match the\n  single-sourced adapter constants.\n- **Teeth:** revert one rewired site to its direct vendor import and confirm the neutrality gate\n  goes RED.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] None of the 12 rewired core modules import `adapters.jira.*` or the root vendor modules,\n  and no direct `AcliClient(` construction remains outside `adapters/jira/` — verified by the\n  neutrality `grep`/test gate returning zero hits.\n- [ ] ADF size-fitting, lossy status/parent mapping, the duplicated value-maps, and the\n  `outbound_links` link constants are single-sourced under `adapters/jira/`; grepping the core\n  sites for those constructs returns zero hits (assertion is core-emptiness + single-sourcing,\n  path-agnostic — the file move itself is S5).\n- [ ] `apply_inbound_records.py` uses `RemoteRef`/`IdentityConvention` with no hardcoded `\"jira\"`\n  provider/creation-channel literal — verified by `grep`.\n- [ ] The **existing** `applier`/`fetcher` `_load_acli` seams pass with the seam now returning\n  the backend transport directly, across **all three** injection styles (`patch.object`,\n  `monkeypatch.setattr`, direct attribute assignment) and the integration `_fakes.py` double —\n  verified by `make test` green (the behavioral oracle). The migration is **complete** (no\n  double left module-shaped) when\n  `grep -Ern 'AcliClient(\\.return_value)?[[:space:]]*=|_FakeAcliModule' tests/ | grep -i acli`\n  (POSIX ERE via `-E`, `[[:space:]]` not GNU-only `\\s`, so it is portable on macOS/BSD grep)\n  returns **zero** hits at the `_load_acli` seam doubles — the `(\\.return_value)?` alternation\n  deliberately also catches the MagicMock module-double form `fake_acli_mod.AcliClient.return_value\n  = fake_client` (used in ~8 applier tests, e.g. `apply/test_applier_stale_binding_404.py`), not\n  only bare `AcliClient =` assignment — i.e. no seam double still exposes an `AcliClient` factory\n  in either style. (No hard file-count assertion — the count is fragile due to the two excluded\n  self-defining `def _load_acli()` files and cross-style overlap.)\n- [ ] `run_differs.py:403` (which had **no** seam — a bare `acli` import + direct\n  `AcliClient(...)`) gets a **new** seam/transport-injection point routed through\n  `select_backend(config).transport`, covered by a **new** test that patches it (no pre-existing\n  patch target) — verified by that new test passing under `make test` and by\n  `grep -rn 'AcliClient(' src/rebar/_engine/rebar_reconciler/run_differs.py` returning zero hits.\n- [ ] `_attestation.py`'s `build_acli_client_from_env()` (`:41`, constructing\n  `mod.AcliClient(jira_url=…, user=…, api_token=…, jira_project=…)` at `:82` for bootstrap-band\n  execution) is rewired to build and return the selected backend's transport\n  (`select_backend(load_config()).transport`, constructed from the same `JIRA_*` env-derived\n  settings), **preserving its fail-fast missing-env behavior**. It is a standalone construction\n  site (no `_load_acli` seam), so its rewire is covered by a **dedicated** test that stubs the\n  backend selection and asserts `build_acli_client_from_env()` returns the transport built from\n  the env `JiraSettings` (and still raises the same error when required env is absent) — verified\n  by that test under `make test` and by\n  `grep -rn 'AcliClient(' src/rebar/_engine/rebar_reconciler/_attestation.py` returning zero hits.\n- [ ] `apply_handlers.py:181` catches `AssigneeNotFoundError` via a direct\n  `from rebar_reconciler.acli_subprocess import AssigneeNotFoundError` (not `ctx.acli.…`), so the\n  assignee soft-fail path still works when `_load_acli()` returns a bare transport — verified by\n  the existing assignee-soft-fail error-path test (`pytest tests/ -k \"assignee and (soft or not_found)\"`, exit 0)\n  and by `grep -n 'ctx.acli.AssigneeNotFoundError' src/rebar/_engine/rebar_reconciler/apply_handlers.py`\n  returning **zero** hits.\n- [ ] The full reconcile characterization suite yields identical outcomes to pre-story `main`;\n  `make lint && make typecheck && make test` all green."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784743644694960001,"uuid":"1185a597-13d2-484d-9dc3-3166c524d851"}